I want to make some optimizations for TK1. @gangm , can you measure the time of this code on your TK1?

```C++
    matrix<unsigned char, 1536, 2048> img;
    dlib::array<array2d<double>> hog;
    chrono::system_clock::time_point start = chrono::system_clock::now();
    impl_fhog::impl_extract_fhog_features(img, hog, 8, 1, 1);
    chrono::system_clock::time_point end = chrono::system_clock::now();
    double msec = std::chrono::duration_cast<chrono::milliseconds>(end - start).count();
    cout << msec << endl;
```

My timings:
1. i7/2.2Ghz (MinGW 6.3/Windows 7x64) AVX = ~45ms
2. i7/2.2Ghz (MinGW 6.3/Windows 7x64) SSE2 = ~100 ms
3. TK1 (GCC6.2) : ~12300 ms
4. TK1 (GCC6.2) -Ofast: ~1100 ms
5. TK1 (GCC6.2) + NEON = ~300 ms

I suggest to use [**jinja**](http://jinja.pocoo.org/) to do the templating.

Something like that:

```jinja
{% title, *body = repository.commit().message.split('\n') %}
### Title
{{ title }}

### Body
{{ '\n'.join(body) }}

{% match = re.match(repository.head.name, '^(\d+)') %}
{% if match %}
closes {{ match.groups()[0] }}
{% endif %}
```

@heitzmann I would like to provide you with an early feedback with regard to gdspy 1.1. I have installed ```gdspy-1.1.win-amd64-py3.5.exe``` using ```WinPython-64bit-3.5.2.2``` on Windows 10 and have run initial checks against our existing libraries. 
The installation part is flawless - everything went smoothly. I appreciate the fact that the code base is now in Python 3.
I have noted that there must have been some functional changes to the ```gdspy.Cell``` class that have prevented our libraries from executing fully. I am seeing exceptions in ```gdspy.Cell.cell_dict```, ```cell.copy```, etc. that we will likely need to modify to comply with the new release.

Made one more fix:
7) else block in numeric parser has unsatisfiable conditions:
```js
if (num > 1 && txt !== '') {
//...
} else {
  word = (txt + '').match(/\d+/g);
  return word && word.length >= num ? word[num - 1] : txt || '';
} 
```
is always performed with `num == 1` or with `txt == ''`. So the result is either full numeric match or an empty string. If it is a numeric match, then match is integer numeric.
For now if `txt` is a float number, it also will be parsed.

If planned functionality (obtain n-th number from a string) is useful, it possibly should be made with another grouper.

