One use case I can see is where you are using JWT for authentication but you also want to provide a way to forcefully disable/log out/unauthenticate a user. As you mentioned you could rely on short JWT expire times, but that might not be enough. I was particularly interested in building a client-side (ember) enhancement that allowed activity based logout where if a user was idle for X seconds, their jwt token was revoked (blacklisted) and they would have to get a new one to log in.

That was my initial thought, not sure what/how others are using it...

If the goal is to auto-cast when possible, then the right way to do that is
```
if not six.PY3 and isinstance(obj, unicode):
    try:
        obj = obj.encode("ascii")
    except UnicodeEncodeError:
        raise PatsyError(...)
```
and it might even go into `ModelDesc.from_formula`. But... while issuing a better error message would obviously be a win, I'm less sure that auto-casting is actually a good idea. Can someone elaborate on the motivation for this? My intuition is that it's not really a convenience for interactive use, because in interactive use no-one is going to be typing `u"y ~ x"` when they could be typing `"y ~ x"` -- so I assume these unicode strings are coming from some other library/framework. And if you have some code that is dealing with unicode strings (esp. on py2), then your only hope of making your code correct is if you have an explicit strategy for dealing with unicode/encoding issues. Should patsy really be making a wild guess at what to do when passed unicode? In what case is this better than raising an error and making the caller think about what they actually want (which may or may not be `.encode("ascii")`)? (This is a real question.)

